bib_record.title: Excitation Functions of 191+193-Ir, 197-Au(6-LI,XN+YP) Compound Nuclear Reactions at E(LI)= 48-156 MeV

free_txt: In-Beam Gamma-Ray Spectra have Been Measured and
Neutron Deficient Isotopes of Au, Hg, Tl and Pb
Have Been Identified from at Least 2 Known
Gamma-Rays.
For the Analysis of the Gamma-Spectra Mostly the
Transitions Feeding the Ground State or an Isomeric
State have Been Used. These Transitions in General
Represent 100% Production Intensity.
.The Experimental Excitation Functions are
Discussed on the Basis of Predictions of Blann'S
Preequilibrium (HYBRID) Model.
In the Energy Scale of the Excitation Functions
Corrections were Necessary According to the Energy
Losses of the Li-6 Ions in the Targets. The Energy
Losses were Estimated and Converted Into an Energy
Shift of the Experimental Points Considered.
Furthermore, Corrections were Applied For Angular
Distribution and For Internal Conversion.
As Stated in a Private Communication, the Authors
Assume an Error in the Normalization As Suggested by
More Recent Experiments. Consequently, the Absolute
Cross Sections have to be Multiplied by a Constant
Factor (GREATER THAN 1), Though the Relative Heights of
The Excitation Functions are Believed to be Correct.
The Energy Resolution was 2.1 KeV, the Relative
Efficiency 15% For the 1332 KeV Gamma-Rays of Co-60.
For the Measured Cross Sections a Total Error
Of 20-25% is Estimated.  Included are Uncertainties
From the Normalization Procedure (17% ), Errors in
Gamma Intensity Determination (5-15%) Including
Statistics  and Uncertainties of Peak Area Analysis, in
Detector Efficiency and Conversion Coefficients (5%
EACH), and in the Gamma-Ray Angular Distribution (<10%)
The Total Energy Uncertainty Varies Between 3 and
5 MeV For Beam Energies from 156 MeV to 48 MeV,
Respectively.
In Beam Spectrometry.
The Primary Li-6 Beam Energy of 156 MeV was
Degraded by be-Absorber Foils in Steps of About
10 MeV Down to E(LI)=48 MeV. Since the Energy Loss
In Beryllium is Known Only For Li-7 Ions Up to an
Energy of 80 MeV, the Energy Loss of Li-7 was
Converted Into That of Li-6 and Extrapolated For
Li-6 Ions of Higher Energies.
To Calculate Absolute Cross Sections the Gamma-Ray
Yields were Normalized to the X-Ray
Intensities Produced by the Projectile-Target
Interaction and Measured Simultaneously with the
Gamma-Rays of the Residual Nuclei.
The Numerical Values were Obtained from the
Authors.
